Very heavy questions.

00:07:29.950 --> 00:07:33.320
What mathematicians
were able to do--

00:07:33.320 --> 00:07:34.265
should I go here?

00:07:34.265 --> 00:07:35.780
OK, I'll go there.

00:07:35.780 --> 00:07:40.320
What mathematicians were able
to do, were able to create

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:45.190
sets of numbers that you
couldn't measure.

00:07:45.190 --> 00:07:47.920
And it was linked to these
kinds of ideas.

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:51.440
So you're actually picking all--
the guy who did it was a

00:07:51.440 --> 00:07:53.650
guy called Giuseppe Vitali.

00:07:53.650 --> 00:07:57.150
And he came up with this idea of
consider the solid segment

00:07:57.150 --> 00:08:01.040
between 0 and 1 and consider
all the fractions.

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:06.670
Then he considered every single
copy of that in 0 to 1.

00:08:06.670 --> 00:08:08.400
And what that means is it's
very complicated.

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:09.430
It's called a partition.

00:08:09.430 --> 00:08:12.450
But basically, he found all
these different copies of it.

00:08:12.450 --> 00:08:15.480
Then he just took one point
from every single copy.

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:18.630
And that set you could
not measure.

00:08:18.630 --> 00:08:22.120
There was no way you could
get a sensible answer.

00:08:22.120 --> 00:08:24.340
Getting 0 is a sensible
answer.

00:08:24.340 --> 00:08:26.160
This gave no sensible answer.

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:27.000
It gave a contradiction.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:28.965
You look at it one way,
you get one answer.

00:08:28.965 --> 00:08:31.850
You look at it the other way,
you get a different answer.

00:08:31.850 --> 00:08:33.470
That's a problem.

00:08:33.470 --> 00:08:35.809
Because I thought I knew
how to measure.

00:08:35.809 --> 00:08:37.700
I thought I knew how
to use a ruler.

00:08:37.700 --> 00:08:39.640
I thought I knew maths.

